WEBVTT

00:03.394 --> 00:03.635
All right.

00:03.815 --> 00:04.496
Good morning, everyone.

00:05.338 --> 00:08.566
One of you just joined me as we prayed just before I kick off.

00:09.788 --> 00:12.414
So, Lord Jesus, thank you that we can come here today.

00:12.434 --> 00:16.503
Lord, thank you that we can come and learn more about you and more about your word together.

00:16.523 --> 00:21.394
Lord, we just pray that Lord, I thank you that you have something that you want to impart to each one of us.

00:21.826 --> 00:25.850
Even if we don't know why we came here this morning, Lord, that you didn't bring us here by accident.

00:26.391 --> 00:28.433
So the weather is that you want us to take from this morning.

00:28.473 --> 00:33.398
I pray that you would just impart that into our hearts or anything that is not from you or not for us.

00:33.518 --> 00:36.681
Just pray that would be just fall away and be lost in Jesus name.

00:37.262 --> 00:38.683
Amen.

00:38.703 --> 00:40.485
All right.

00:40.826 --> 00:46.812
Well, I got open with a short story this morning just for a few minutes.

00:47.112 --> 00:49.074
And it's a story of something that happened to me

00:49.186 --> 00:51.810
Oh, gosh, 12 years ago.

00:52.371 --> 00:53.813
Yes, so 2014, 12 years ago.

00:54.535 --> 01:03.689
And so I just finished medical school and got a fresh out and I went off to what's called a medical elective, which is something you do after you graduated.

01:03.710 --> 01:11.783
You get to spend a couple of months working somewhere else and some of my friends went to Australia or all lovely places and I went to work at Aclinic in Haiti.

01:12.764 --> 01:16.370
And this was three years after the 2010 earthquakes had happened.

01:16.514 --> 01:21.201
And it was, I think, something like 50% of the buildings there was still flat.

01:21.361 --> 01:25.428
It was quite a humbling and heartbreaking experience.

01:27.290 --> 01:33.099
But before I even got there, I never actually treated a patient as a real doctor before.

01:33.119 --> 01:34.001
I hadn't actually done anything.

01:34.642 --> 01:40.971
And I was half asleep on my plane on the way over from America, and then kind of connecting flight down to Haiti.

01:41.693 --> 01:45.298
And there was a voice that came over the Tanoy.

01:45.890 --> 01:50.277
They said, is there a doctor on the plane?

01:50.337 --> 01:54.784
And I know some people, some people I went to med school with, they would have loved this.

01:54.864 --> 01:56.046
They would have lived for this.

01:56.086 --> 01:57.889
This would have been their moment.

01:57.909 --> 02:00.173
They would have cracked their fingers and cracked on.

02:00.653 --> 02:10.309
And I was gripped by an icy cold fear and terror unlike anything that I can quite explain before or since.

02:11.090 --> 02:13.554
And we were in the middle of the Atlantic Ocean.

02:13.634 --> 02:16.216
And I was there, and I was sitting there, and I was going to follow up around.

02:16.236 --> 02:18.158
I was like, oh my gosh, what's going to happen?

02:18.238 --> 02:19.259
What are they going to ask me to do?

02:19.640 --> 02:20.901
Like, am I going to get it wrong?

02:20.941 --> 02:21.702
Are they going to ask me?

02:21.722 --> 02:22.743
Are we going to have to land the plane?

02:22.763 --> 02:23.724
What if it's the pilot?

02:23.784 --> 02:25.726
What if they ask me to land the plane?

02:26.086 --> 02:27.347
No, that's not very likely.

02:27.387 --> 02:32.112
But I was like, just all these things were going round and round and round in my head.

02:32.572 --> 02:34.514
And they said it again.

02:34.534 --> 02:35.775
Is there a doctor on the plane?

02:35.795 --> 02:37.116
So I was like, surely someone else will go.

02:37.237 --> 02:37.997
And nobody moved.

02:38.037 --> 02:39.619
And I was like, cool.

02:39.859 --> 02:42.962
OK, this one must be for me.

02:43.106 --> 02:51.737
So I stood up very kind of nervously and I walked over to the kind of the air sheared and I said, oh, you know, I'm a doctor.

02:52.438 --> 02:55.722
And I kid you not, she looked at me and she laughed at me.

02:56.283 --> 02:59.947
Like, I'm not joking and she told me to sit down.

03:00.007 --> 03:05.394
And I'm assuming, the only reason I can assume it, I assume this happened,

03:05.474 --> 03:28.016
is that it was an American airline, medicine's a postgraduate thing I think in America and so you have to be kind of 28, 29 and I was 23 and I looked about 17 and I didn't have a bid and so I totally, I do understand and the only way I managed to actually convince her was I had kind of a load of medical stuff in my hand luggage and I was like look either I brought this on the off chance that this happened so that I could kind of pose as a doctor or this is really true.

03:28.777 --> 03:33.682
And she let me through and actually what I'd been called to see was kind of

03:33.826 --> 03:37.170
was kind of a bit something or nothing, you know, they've got all this kit, but I've no idea what to do with any of it.

03:37.951 --> 03:44.718
But thankfully, there's somebody there, they're kind of a little bit in and out of consciousness and actually, I don't know, maybe they've taken a bit too much of something to calm down before the flight.

03:45.319 --> 03:50.805
It was all fine, kind of sat with them for about 20 minutes, and then they woke up and I went and sat back down.

03:52.687 --> 03:55.830
But what I remember from that experience was the fear.

03:56.951 --> 03:59.534
The fear, the feeling, what if I get it wrong?

04:00.315 --> 04:01.376
What if I'm not good enough?

04:01.636 --> 04:03.058
What if I don't know enough?

04:03.650 --> 04:05.793
What if I don't have enough experience?

04:06.054 --> 04:08.277
Somebody else must be better.

04:09.259 --> 04:11.442
There must be someone else who can do this.

04:12.424 --> 04:13.546
And why am I telling you this story?

04:13.626 --> 04:21.298
Well, we're looking at the moment at this theme that kind of started on kind of the worship and testimony Sunday, first Sunday of January.

04:21.598 --> 04:25.024
And it's moved through Vision Sunday and into kind of Bev speaking last week.

04:25.124 --> 04:29.170
And it's all around this idea of stepping into the story.

04:30.306 --> 04:39.336
Because Nicky spoke on Vision Sunday about how the year just gone has been an amazing year, but it's been a hard year for lots of us as well.

04:40.117 --> 04:43.620
But it feels like as a church, we're stepping into a new era.

04:43.680 --> 04:48.265
And part of stepping into that new era is this thing of stepping into the story.

04:49.367 --> 04:50.368
We want to get involved.

04:50.868 --> 04:51.569
We want to be ready.

04:51.589 --> 04:54.192
We don't want to miss out on what God is doing.

04:55.073 --> 04:59.858
But if we want to step in, we're probably going to have to deal with all of those feelings that I was feeling

05:00.066 --> 05:02.229
on that plane over the Atlantic.

05:02.890 --> 05:03.972
That, I can't do it.

05:04.593 --> 05:05.234
I couldn't do it.

05:06.395 --> 05:07.016
I'm too weak.

05:07.377 --> 05:08.078
I'm inadequate.

05:08.138 --> 05:08.799
I'm not enough.

05:09.500 --> 05:11.222
Thinking about what could happen.

05:11.242 --> 05:12.524
What's the worst that could go wrong?

05:12.544 --> 05:13.666
I'll get it wrong.

05:13.686 --> 05:14.387
I'll mess it up.

05:14.407 --> 05:15.889
I'll look stupid.

05:16.811 --> 05:21.978
There must be someone better or maybe even just everyone will laugh at me.

05:23.200 --> 05:24.843
Because our own fear keeps us sidelined.

05:25.524 --> 05:27.186
It disqualifies us from stepping in.

05:27.906 --> 05:30.590
We say it could never be me because of this or because of that.

05:32.333 --> 05:33.815
But it isn't about feeling ready.

05:34.316 --> 05:36.860
It's about hearing God and trusting God.

05:37.962 --> 05:44.632
And maybe sometimes I'm worried that I'll get it wrong and God will look bad, but far more of the time I'm worried that I'll get it wrong and I'll look bad.

05:45.754 --> 05:48.899
And so I'm going to start with my overall point here.

05:48.919 --> 05:50.942
So if you want to have a nap for the next 20 minutes, that's fine.

05:50.962 --> 05:52.685
But make sure you remember this before you do.

05:53.567 --> 05:55.730
If you want to step into the story,

05:56.162 --> 06:08.194
We're gonna have to get used to the fact that we might have to risk looking silly, getting it wrong, messing up, looking weak, not starting from a place of strength and not having it all together.

06:09.955 --> 06:12.938
And thankfully, that's okay.

06:12.958 --> 06:21.046
Two Corinthians 12, 19 says, but he said to me, my grace is sufficient for you, for my power is made perfect in weakness.

06:21.947 --> 06:25.170
Therefore, I will boast all the more gladly about my weaknesses

06:25.378 --> 06:28.322
so that Christ's power may rest on me.

06:30.004 --> 06:30.705
I'll put it another way.

06:31.807 --> 06:37.294
What if the biggest barrier to us stepping into the story isn't the fact that I'm weak?

06:38.095 --> 06:43.462
It's the fact that I don't trust that God will use my weakness for his glory.

06:44.784 --> 06:47.568
So I put it to each one of us here in the silence of our own hearts.

06:48.729 --> 06:52.114
Do we really trust that God can use our weaknesses?

06:52.642 --> 06:58.030
not those kind of weaknesses that we might say in an interview that are really strengths, like, oh my gosh, I'm too perfect.

06:58.270 --> 07:02.617
I'm just too obsessed with time management, not one of those, but our genuine weaknesses.

07:04.219 --> 07:07.704
Do we really trust that God can use our weaknesses for his glory?

07:08.385 --> 07:13.753
Because he absolutely can, and he absolutely will if we are brave enough to let him.

07:14.895 --> 07:16.978
And I could, could probably just leave it there.

07:17.602 --> 07:20.967
But Kate and Anita told me they got lots of stuff planned for kids and planned for youth.

07:20.987 --> 07:25.052
So I'm going to press on at least for a few minutes because I'd hate to rob them of the amazing stuff that's happening.

07:25.072 --> 07:28.397
And there is, there is some amazing stuff that's happening in kids and in youth.

07:28.597 --> 07:33.744
And Claire mentioned on Friday night, 350 youth and young people here worshiping.

07:33.824 --> 07:37.650
If you want to be inspired by what God is doing, have a chat with Kate.

07:37.690 --> 07:38.491
Have a chat with Anita.

07:38.511 --> 07:39.512
They are doing amazing work.

07:39.572 --> 07:42.636
And God is doing amazing stuff in our kids and our youth.

07:42.656 --> 07:43.858
So if you want to be inspired,

07:44.258 --> 07:45.780
have a chat with them after the service.

07:45.800 --> 07:49.225
They would love to tell you a bit more about what is going on.

07:52.209 --> 07:55.013
So I was reflecting on this idea of stepping into the story.

07:55.094 --> 07:56.976
And someone, someone very wise asked me a question.

07:57.016 --> 07:57.737
I was prepping this.

07:57.797 --> 07:59.940
They said, whose story is it that we're stepping into?

08:01.342 --> 08:03.365
Well, ultimately, it's Jesus's story.

08:03.526 --> 08:08.833
It's the kingdom story that is being written across the whole world throughout time.

08:09.755 --> 08:12.178
But like all good stories, there are branches.

08:13.026 --> 08:16.231
There's a story that God is writing in each one of us individually.

08:16.692 --> 08:20.277
The fact that we get to partner with Jesus in building this big story.

08:22.020 --> 08:24.604
There's a story here at Scarlet Church that's being written.

08:25.265 --> 08:28.189
And we're involved by virtue of sitting in the seats or being here.

08:28.229 --> 08:30.653
We're involved for however long or however short that is.

08:31.314 --> 08:38.004
And then there's this world kind of kingdom story that is being written by God through millions of churches and through billions of Christians.

08:39.006 --> 08:41.650
Even people who don't know him, God is writing

08:41.730 --> 08:44.172
a story in each of our lives.

08:45.313 --> 08:51.980
And I say this, because the story, when we think of stepping into the story, the story is about what is happening here.

08:52.060 --> 08:55.443
But I want to be clear, it's not just what about what is happening here.

08:56.224 --> 09:04.732
It's not just about the amazing stuff that we get to do, or kids' volunteers, or even people who uproot their lives and start an AIDS hospital in Uganda.

09:04.792 --> 09:07.995
And all of that stuff is good, and it might be part of your story.

09:09.997 --> 09:11.538
But it's not just about

09:11.650 --> 09:40.370
that because God writes a story in each of us individually and we have the choice to say yes I'm up for it or we have the choice to push against it and run away and I'm sure we have all done that at times I have definitely done that at times and God is gracious and God always keeps giving us more chances keeps giving me more chances when I say no or when I disqualify myself but I am making it harder but I want to look at

09:40.482 --> 09:43.546
a story this morning that demonstrates this and boil down a bit deeper.

09:43.606 --> 09:46.530
So we're going to look at a story in the book of judges.

09:47.091 --> 09:56.123
And I like judges because it gives me hope because I can really feel that like in my own life, the book of judges is a series of cycles.

09:57.205 --> 10:00.149
It's a story of Israel inhabiting the promised land.

10:00.790 --> 10:04.955
God has bought them through the wilderness, but they aren't living the way that he's told them to.

10:05.076 --> 10:06.678
And so it's all gone a bit to part, to be honest.

10:07.319 --> 10:09.842
And they're stuck in this cycle.

10:09.954 --> 10:11.777
of sin, turning away from God.

10:12.899 --> 10:13.680
Everything goes wrong.

10:14.602 --> 10:16.665
They're oppressed by their sins and by their neighbours.

10:17.547 --> 10:21.854
They cry out to God for forgiveness and for help.

10:21.874 --> 10:30.548
And God sends a rescuer, a leader that's called a judge, and they save them from whatever's going on and the tribes and whatever and they repent, and then everything's okay.

10:31.029 --> 10:32.612
And then the cycle repeats.

10:32.832 --> 10:33.874
I don't know if

10:34.498 --> 10:49.034
If any of you can feel any of that cycle in your own life, but I can definitely feel that cycle in mind of crying out to God, finding God in something, figuring out a new way of getting it wrong, and then having to come back to God all over again.

10:50.255 --> 10:55.581
And the judges, the judges that Jesus uses, they aren't perfect by any stretch, and some of them are downright awful.

10:56.442 --> 10:59.325
But all of them are used by God despite their flaws.

10:59.385 --> 11:03.730
And we're gonna look this morning at a particular judge, a man called Gideon.

11:04.386 --> 11:06.708
So we're here for the story.

11:06.748 --> 11:08.590
Israelites have been brought into the Promised Land.

11:08.810 --> 11:10.993
Moses has led them out of Egypt through the wilderness.

11:11.173 --> 11:11.633
He's dead.

11:12.374 --> 11:15.257
Joshua settled in the Promised Land with them at the beginning of Judges.

11:15.297 --> 11:15.978
He's dead too.

11:16.738 --> 11:24.566
And there's a group of pretty dreadful people who are living in the land called Canaanites, which is a bit of a casual term for everybody who's there in the land.

11:25.167 --> 11:27.509
And God has said to them, get rid of these people.

11:27.870 --> 11:29.091
This is your land.

11:29.151 --> 11:32.114
You don't want them here because you're going to become

11:32.194 --> 11:33.015
like them.

11:33.095 --> 11:39.124
And they were a pretty awful bunch and there were sacrifices and idol worship and all kind of horrific things that were happening.

11:39.966 --> 11:44.132
So God said, get rid of them or you'll become like them.

11:44.152 --> 11:44.833
But they haven't done it.

11:45.053 --> 11:50.080
They started doing it and then somewhere along the way they kind of run out of steam and it gets hard to get rid of them.

11:50.101 --> 11:54.928
And so they decide rather than actually get rid of them, they're going to keep them around and they're going to put them to work instead.

11:57.031 --> 11:59.955
And in so doing, they end up becoming just like them.

12:00.957 --> 12:01.938
It's pretty awful.

12:02.210 --> 12:02.611
people.

12:02.711 --> 12:07.079
They forget God, they worship false idols, and they start with pagan practices.

12:08.041 --> 12:12.469
And ultimately, there's nothing that separates them as the people of God from the people around them.

12:13.591 --> 12:16.276
They lose their identity as the people of God.

12:18.279 --> 12:19.061
And I was reading through this.

12:19.121 --> 12:20.003
I'm thinking, how?

12:20.463 --> 12:21.245
How does that happen?

12:21.305 --> 12:24.050
How do you go through a journey where you're led

12:24.162 --> 12:27.726
through the wilderness by a pillar of fire and a cloud of smoke.

12:27.786 --> 12:35.776
How do you see such powerful manifestations of God with bread and manna and then still end up looking like everyone else around you?

12:37.178 --> 12:40.742
And then I think about how much I look just like the culture around me.

12:42.004 --> 12:53.938
Rather than looking like Jesus, as I'm called to do, despite everything he's done for me and everything that I've seen him do in my life, it's so easy to just look like everyone else.

12:54.690 --> 12:59.314
And don't get me wrong, Jesus calls us in John 17 that we're called to be in the world.

12:59.915 --> 13:06.561
And I love, I love that there is so many bits of our culture here in Skylark, here in the UK, here in 2026, there's so many things that I love.

13:06.901 --> 13:13.948
So I'm not suggesting that we go out and start driving our neighbours from our homes or shutting ourselves off from the world with our fingers in our ears because it doesn't all look like us.

13:15.770 --> 13:18.853
But we're called to be in the world, not of the world.

13:19.694 --> 13:24.498
And all too often, my highest priorities look the same as the highest priorities of the world.

13:24.738 --> 13:26.360
rather than the priorities of heaven.

13:27.581 --> 13:32.547
Safety, comfort, financial security, power, success.

13:33.689 --> 13:41.899
Maybe some of the darker ones, greed, selfishness, a desire to just kind of warm myself in with my own little comforts and get on with my own little life.

13:43.320 --> 13:47.826
Because it's too easy for my priorities to look just like everyone else.

13:49.488 --> 13:54.514
So when I ask how could it happen to the people of God, I know because it happens to me.

13:55.010 --> 13:59.856
It might be a different culture, but it's the same heart that we struggle with.

14:01.238 --> 14:05.703
And the book of Judges sums up this whole kind of state of affairs really well.

14:06.304 --> 14:09.067
They say these words, and they're repeated later throughout the chapter in the book.

14:09.888 --> 14:13.493
It says, in those days, Israel had no king.

14:14.754 --> 14:18.539
All the people did whatever seemed right in their own eyes.

14:20.401 --> 14:24.466
And I think that's probably as relevant today as it was then.

14:25.762 --> 14:26.723
And so that's the backdrop.

14:27.064 --> 14:29.126
In Israel, they have a few of these cycles.

14:29.447 --> 14:32.230
And the first few judges that come in, they were pretty good.

14:32.490 --> 14:33.431
To be honest, they were pretty great.

14:34.152 --> 14:36.075
But they're only human, and eventually they die.

14:36.475 --> 14:38.558
And what happens is Israel goes right back to its old way.

14:38.578 --> 14:44.685
So, the judge comes in, everything's okay, the judge goes away, people suddenly forget everything that's happened, and the cycle repeats.

14:45.807 --> 14:55.058
And there is something in that, as I was reflecting on it, there is something in that, at how much the faith of the nation of Israel relied on its human leaders who were there.

14:55.394 --> 14:55.995
at the time.

14:58.338 --> 15:01.582
Because in 2026, we have access to so much.

15:02.343 --> 15:04.827
There are online services.

15:04.847 --> 15:05.848
There are big churches.

15:05.868 --> 15:07.010
There are big worship leaders.

15:07.030 --> 15:08.792
There are big name pastors.

15:08.892 --> 15:15.762
And there is a sense of this celebrity Christian culture because people are so accessible.

15:15.862 --> 15:17.444
Rightly or wrongly, people are so accessible.

15:18.125 --> 15:19.847
And there's so many people who are doing amazing things.

15:19.907 --> 15:20.408
Don't get me wrong.

15:20.588 --> 15:23.011
These amazing leaders that you see are doing amazing things.

15:23.072 --> 15:24.914
And we have amazing leaders here at home.

15:25.026 --> 15:32.335
Pete Nikki and the others who lead us, it is such a blessing to us as a church and as a network and none of that is bad, please hear me right.

15:33.196 --> 15:39.283
But it does feel like we need to ask the question, who do we follow primarily for each of us individually?

15:40.064 --> 15:48.114
Because the risk of having amazing people that we can see is that we can start following them rather than following Jesus.

15:49.378 --> 15:50.800
And that doesn't mean that they're doing anything wrong.

15:50.820 --> 15:52.922
That doesn't mean that they're not following Jesus with us.

15:52.983 --> 16:03.776
It's very easy rather than have a relationship with Jesus ourselves to have a relationship with Jesus by proxy through somebody else that we see who seems to be getting it right.

16:09.523 --> 16:10.585
And we don't want to be people.

16:11.226 --> 16:17.874
I don't want to be a person whose faith relies on anybody else apart from Jesus.

16:19.618 --> 16:26.190
And so I think that's how the nations of Israel at this time, they find their judge and the judge goes and they just go back to the railways.

16:26.331 --> 16:28.214
Let's not be a church like that.

16:28.274 --> 16:33.745
Let's make sure that our relationships with Jesus are our relationships with Jesus, not relationships by proxy.

16:36.069 --> 16:38.674
Anyway, Gideon, here we are.

16:39.618 --> 16:48.427
So we're going to start a judges six, and the whole story runs judges six to eight, and we aren't going to read the whole thing, but I'm going to skip through a couple of points which I'll put on the screen.

16:49.268 --> 16:52.611
And yeah, so versus what, sorry, where are we?

16:53.932 --> 16:55.314
Yes, sorry, judges six.

16:55.894 --> 16:58.877
Verse one to six, on the screen, amplified Bible.

17:02.020 --> 17:07.826
Then the Israelites did evil in the sight of the Lord, and the Lord gave them into the hand of Midian for seven years.

17:08.386 --> 17:11.049
The powerful hand of Midian prevailed against Israel.

17:11.889 --> 17:17.935
Because of Midian, the sons of Israel made for themselves the dens which were in the mountains and the caves and the strongholds.

17:18.936 --> 17:26.343
For it was whenever Israel had sown their seat that the Midianites would come up with the Amalekites and the people of the east and go up against them.

17:27.524 --> 17:37.714
So they would camp against them and destroy the crops of the land as far as Gaza and leave no sustenance in Israel, as well as no sheep, ox, or donkey.

17:38.242 --> 17:46.030
for they would come up with their livestock and their tenets, and they would come into as numerous land as locusts, but they and their camels were innumerable.

17:46.991 --> 17:48.893
So they came into the land to devastate it.

17:49.934 --> 17:56.440
And Israel was greatly impoverished because of the Midianites, and the Israelites cried out to the Lord for help.

17:56.761 --> 17:58.122
Thank you, Martin, for following me along there.

18:00.685 --> 18:02.106
So here's the beginning of the cycle.

18:02.867 --> 18:03.668
Israel does evil.

18:04.448 --> 18:05.970
God allows them to be overtaken.

18:06.594 --> 18:10.118
and these other groups by the Midianites, these other groups that travel through the land.

18:10.398 --> 18:21.169
And this is a repeated cycle and we're told they are so numerous that they are like locusts and Israel is so impoverished and fearful every harvest because they see what they're growing being stolen away from them.

18:22.890 --> 18:28.656
And we heard Pete talk on Vision Sunday about all the amazing stuff that's been happening here as a church in the last year.

18:29.577 --> 18:34.322
And so as a church, I don't feel like we are seeing our harvest being stolen.

18:35.074 --> 18:38.279
But as we've already acknowledged, last year was a hard year for a lot of people.

18:39.020 --> 18:42.325
And I think on an individual level, it can definitely feel a bit like this.

18:43.286 --> 18:46.391
That our joys seem to be stolen by the things in life that come against us.

18:47.392 --> 18:53.641
And the desire to hide in the caves and the mountains and just get by and ignore the dangers is a very real one.

18:54.643 --> 18:57.868
To batten down the hatches and just get through what's coming.

19:00.331 --> 19:03.055
Because they're hiding in their own land.

19:04.257 --> 19:04.818
And why?

19:05.570 --> 19:10.916
Because when God said to remove the things that weren't good for them, they left the job half dumb.

19:13.159 --> 19:23.831
If God says I need to remove something out of my life, sin or temptation or a problem, if I half do the job inevitably, it's gonna come back and bite me.

19:24.872 --> 19:31.560
Sorry, don't give me a glass of water, sorry.

19:31.580 --> 19:33.202
Thank you very much, my glamorous assistant.

19:40.834 --> 19:43.798
Sorry about that.

19:43.818 --> 19:44.900
So that's where Israel is.

19:45.981 --> 19:47.463
The whole people are terrified.

19:47.924 --> 19:50.668
Nobody wants to stick their head up above the parapet.

19:50.688 --> 19:51.909
And we zoom into this lens.

19:51.929 --> 19:53.331
This one man called Gideon.

19:53.351 --> 19:55.655
And we pick up his story at verse 11.

19:57.137 --> 20:04.487
Now, the angel of the Lord came and sat under the terra-binth tree at Orphra, which belonged to Joash the Abbe-Zurite.

20:05.228 --> 20:09.554
And his son Gideon was beating wheat in the winepress instead of the thrashing floor.

20:10.274 --> 20:12.156
to hide it and save it from the Midianites.

20:12.737 --> 20:17.782
And the angel of the Lord appeared to him and said, the Lord is with you, O brave man.

20:19.504 --> 20:22.587
So Gideon is beating wheat in a wine press.

20:23.949 --> 20:36.562
Probably most of us aren't particularly familiar with this process, but beating wheat or threshing needs to be done outdoors and needs to be done on high and exposed ground, that picture on the left view.

20:37.250 --> 20:42.115
In order to blow the lighter chaff away, the wind kind of blows it away and keeps the grain.

20:42.655 --> 20:46.159
And wine presses, by comparison on the other side, are sunk into the rock.

20:46.499 --> 20:47.700
They're protected from the elements.

20:47.720 --> 20:48.401
There is no wind.

20:48.441 --> 21:00.473
They are there to try and protect everything from the elements, which means that Gideon is basically going to be picking out individual bits of grain because he is so afraid of being seen.

21:01.454 --> 21:02.915
He is in survival mode.

21:02.975 --> 21:06.098
He is desperate to not make himself a target.

21:07.138 --> 21:16.191
But even in his hiding, the angel of the Lord finds him, which brings me to this first Gideon point that God calls us even when we are hiding.

21:17.413 --> 21:18.314
Gideon is out of sight.

21:18.995 --> 21:22.921
He's doing his own thing, and he's desperately, desperately trying not to be noticed.

21:23.442 --> 21:26.426
He doesn't want to make himself a target, and he just wants to get by.

21:27.828 --> 21:33.577
He's not looking, he's not looking to step in, particularly because that will make him a target and get him killed.

21:34.518 --> 21:37.042
He's accepted the culture of fear that's around him,

21:37.282 --> 21:38.864
and the fact that things are dreadful.

21:39.345 --> 21:42.148
It doesn't feel like there's anything that you can do apart from hide.

21:43.970 --> 21:46.894
But Gideon goes to find him where he's at.

21:46.914 --> 21:49.237
He's not put off by the fact that Gideon is hiding.

21:50.138 --> 21:53.042
He doesn't wait for Gideon to feel ready to come to him.

21:54.283 --> 22:05.938
And there's an encouragement and a challenge here, I think, that even if we're in a place where we feel like we can't step in, we can't risk making a target ourselves and we just want to hide.

22:06.754 --> 22:10.098
That doesn't mean that God isn't going to ask us to do something.

22:11.120 --> 22:21.953
But it also means that no matter how much we feel like we need to hide away, God can always use us because God calls us even when we are hiding.

22:31.405 --> 22:33.247
And God calls us even when we're afraid.

22:34.109 --> 22:35.250
Gideon's pretty scared here.

22:35.778 --> 22:39.082
To be hiding in this wine press, he is terrified.

22:39.963 --> 22:42.205
But what does the angel of the Lord say when he comes to see him?

22:42.986 --> 22:48.472
He doesn't say, strap on your big boy pants Gideon, stop acting like such a coward, get over yourself.

22:49.112 --> 22:52.676
He says, the Lord is with you, oh brave man.

22:54.198 --> 22:57.742
Just to be clear, these are not the actions of a brave man, not by a long shot.

22:58.643 --> 23:05.490
But within the heart of a coward, God sees how he can use Gideon and calls that thing out in him.

23:07.394 --> 23:14.924
He doesn't seem brave, but in his human weaknesses, God names within him the things that he can use for his glory.

23:15.966 --> 23:20.292
Because when God speaks things, they become true.

23:21.173 --> 23:23.837
Because I can say, I can stand up and say something, it may or may not be true.

23:24.458 --> 23:26.981
The sky is blue, hopefully we can agree is true, maybe not.

23:27.882 --> 23:29.845
But if I say the sky is green, that's a lie.

23:30.846 --> 23:36.434
I can speak truth, but what the truth is isn't dependent on what I say, but what is.

23:37.506 --> 23:46.540
But when God speaks, when he says things, what he says becomes true by the fact that he is the definer of truth.

23:47.482 --> 23:51.088
God says, let there be light, and there was light because he said it.

23:52.590 --> 23:54.213
Jesus said, your sins are forgiven.

23:54.293 --> 23:55.655
Go and get up and walk.

23:55.775 --> 24:01.023
And because he said it, a man was paralyzed no longer, and he walked away, and his life was changed forever.

24:02.225 --> 24:05.170
The angel of the Lord says to Gideon, brave man,

24:05.314 --> 24:08.438
Before he has done anything, even remotely brave.

24:09.780 --> 24:16.268
So his bravery comes not from his own strength, but because God has said so.

24:16.288 --> 24:17.530
And you might be feeling like this today.

24:17.911 --> 24:20.254
You might be feeling like you're hiding, like you're scared.

24:21.595 --> 24:23.698
God can't use me because I'm afraid.

24:25.120 --> 24:25.701
I don't know enough.

24:26.181 --> 24:26.882
I'm not brave enough.

24:27.643 --> 24:28.545
I'm not experienced enough.

24:29.025 --> 24:29.506
I'm not ready.

24:31.088 --> 24:32.690
But when God puts something on your heart,

24:33.218 --> 24:36.702
something that he wants you to do, might be a big thing, might be a small thing, might be a tiny thing.

24:37.483 --> 24:45.151
But when that Holy Spirit nudge comes that says, you are the person for this task, none of that matters because God has named that within you.

24:46.092 --> 24:53.280
And there's this really well-known quote, and I'm sure many of you will have heard it, and I couldn't actually find who said it originally, but it goes like this.

24:53.380 --> 24:56.903
God doesn't call the qualified, he qualifies the called.

24:58.265 --> 25:03.090
God doesn't call the qualified, he qualifies the called, because God calls us.

25:03.330 --> 25:05.172
even when we are afraid.

25:07.614 --> 25:11.958
So he's hiding, he's afraid, but that still doesn't disqualify him in God's eyes.

25:12.079 --> 25:14.261
And so we read on from verse 14.

25:15.962 --> 25:21.668
But Gideon said to him, please, my Lord, if the Lord is with us, then why has all this happened to us?

25:22.949 --> 25:32.018
Where are all his wondrous works, which our fathers told us about, when they said, do not, did not the Lord bring us up from Egypt, but now the Lord has abandoned us,

25:32.162 --> 25:33.864
and put us into the hands of Midian.

25:35.405 --> 25:41.132
The Lord turned to him and said, go in this strength of yours and save Israel from the hand of Midian.

25:41.913 --> 25:43.374
Have I not sent you?

25:44.455 --> 25:47.438
But Gideon said to him, please Lord, how am I to rescue Israel?

25:48.119 --> 25:54.006
Behold, my family is the least significant imminator, and I am the youngest and smallest in my father's house.

25:56.548 --> 25:57.930
Gideon is doubting now.

25:58.871 --> 26:01.874
He's got a long old list of doubts, but thankfully,

26:02.146 --> 26:04.669
God can still call us even when we are doubting.

26:05.750 --> 26:06.891
Because first of all, he doubts God.

26:07.853 --> 26:10.996
You know, God, where all these wondrous works that our fathers told us about.

26:11.877 --> 26:14.200
In essence, he's saying, we heard how good it used to be.

26:14.921 --> 26:16.563
But God, if you're with us, why isn't it like that now?

26:17.323 --> 26:19.426
Why are the glories that we used to hear about?

26:19.466 --> 26:21.108
Why aren't we seeing those at the moment?

26:21.168 --> 26:22.369
Why isn't it like it used to be?

26:24.352 --> 26:27.415
And I wonder, do we ever long for a time when things felt a bit easier?

26:28.356 --> 26:29.938
Well, maybe it was all going better.

26:30.082 --> 26:33.527
Or it just felt like God's plan was a bit clearer and a bit more active.

26:34.629 --> 26:37.894
God, why don't we see what we saw last year or 10 years ago?

26:39.776 --> 26:43.702
But as Bev reminded us so beautifully last week, we can't live on yesterday's manner.

26:44.664 --> 26:49.130
And what God wanted to do yesterday isn't necessarily what God wants to do in us today.

26:52.095 --> 26:53.577
And then Gideon, he doubts himself.

26:54.879 --> 26:55.580
I'm the smallest.

26:55.660 --> 26:57.042
I'm the least significant.

26:57.963 --> 26:59.666
As the youngest son, he would have been

26:59.842 --> 27:00.142
young.

27:00.183 --> 27:07.875
He would have had the least power, the least influence, and the smallest family would have had the smallest army and the least number of fighting men.

27:10.218 --> 27:12.803
But we can draw hope in how God responds to Gideon.

27:13.884 --> 27:19.253
Go in this strength of yours and save Israel from the hand of Midian.

27:19.914 --> 27:22.578
Have I not sent you?

27:27.874 --> 27:28.495
And I love this.

27:28.795 --> 27:33.622
And I love it, because this is exactly the opposite of how this scene would go if it was a Hollywood movie.

27:34.203 --> 27:38.009
Because if it was a Hollywood movie, here, we would have a training montage.

27:38.069 --> 27:42.515
So it would be, think, Rocky IV, or the Karate Kid, or Hercules, or Mulan.

27:42.695 --> 27:44.458
This is where the training montage would go.

27:44.918 --> 27:49.926
Because you'd have Gideon bench pressing a sheep in his wine press, or running through the desert with rocks on his back or something.

27:49.946 --> 27:50.286
I don't know.

27:51.087 --> 27:52.389
But there'd be this period of time.

27:52.650 --> 27:54.532
Who knows what they did in that time to work out?

27:54.552 --> 27:55.794
I'm not sure.

27:55.970 --> 28:02.078
But there would be this period of time where we would see Gideon's called and then he becomes who it is that he's called to be.

28:02.639 --> 28:05.723
And because that takes a long time, there would be a montage.

28:05.923 --> 28:14.234
So as the audience, we wouldn't have to sit through, you know, watching him do 100,000 press ups or whatever to get to the point where he was strong enough, clever enough, brave enough to save Israel.

28:14.755 --> 28:16.237
But that's not what we see.

28:17.298 --> 28:22.886
God says, go in the strength that you have, have I not sent you.

28:24.047 --> 28:24.648
And I love that.

28:25.329 --> 28:25.970
I love that.

28:27.010 --> 28:28.172
because you're already brave enough.

28:29.073 --> 28:30.155
You're already strong enough.

28:30.195 --> 28:33.039
Not because you're brave, he's hiding, he's hiding in a wine press.

28:33.780 --> 28:41.191
It's not because he's strong or powerful, because we know he is the smallest, from the smallest family and the youngest son.

28:42.433 --> 28:52.629
But none of that matters, because God's power is made perfect here in Gideon's weaknesses, because God calls us even when we are weak.

28:54.832 --> 28:56.114
And if you're sitting here today,

28:56.386 --> 28:58.548
and you're doubting your ability to step into the story.

28:59.730 --> 29:01.071
Maybe you don't think you know enough.

29:01.712 --> 29:02.533
You aren't wise enough.

29:03.093 --> 29:04.595
You haven't read your Bible enough.

29:05.856 --> 29:09.060
If God is sending you, then none of that matters.

29:10.782 --> 29:16.508
And unfortunately, we can't use it as an excuse to put off until tomorrow what God would have us do today.

29:16.548 --> 29:22.515
And I'm not saying, let's do everything that we're bad at straight away.

29:22.835 --> 29:25.458
If you wanna play guitar in worship,

29:25.698 --> 29:26.899
But you can't play the guitar.

29:27.460 --> 29:30.964
Odds are you're probably not gonna be the right person to come and play the guitar next Sunday.

29:31.064 --> 29:34.228
Doesn't mean you never will be, but it is probably going to take some time.

29:36.111 --> 29:38.614
But it's easy to see someone who's hurting this morning.

29:39.655 --> 29:43.980
And when that Holy Spirit nudge comes to think, I can help them.

29:45.041 --> 29:46.263
I can pray with them today.

29:46.303 --> 29:47.504
I don't pray well.

29:48.906 --> 29:49.807
I don't have the right words.

29:51.169 --> 29:55.474
Or to sit next to somebody new this morning and think, I'm not much for people person.

29:56.418 --> 29:58.401
someone else can make them feel welcome.

30:00.565 --> 30:07.176
When we feel that nudge from Holy Spirit to go and do, it's not about our doubts for today or how great we can be tomorrow.

30:08.718 --> 30:11.503
It's not about getting to the point where we can do it all in our own strength.

30:12.605 --> 30:16.391
It's allowing him to use what we have in the way that he wants.

30:18.354 --> 30:23.122
God calls us even when we are doubting, even when we are weak.

30:31.938 --> 30:35.583
And then I'm conscious of time, so I'm just going to press on.

30:35.843 --> 30:40.310
So we come to this next bit, where Gideon's really wavering.

30:40.350 --> 30:47.440
He's stepped in, and he's done a few things, and those things have gone really well, but he's really starting to wave now, because the stakes have risen.

30:48.822 --> 30:51.846
People are looking like, it's not become academic, it's not theoretical anymore.

30:51.866 --> 30:55.831
He's broken down some idols from the hometown that he lives in.

30:56.653 --> 31:00.498
And there are real consequences to this story now, because people are coming to kill him.

31:00.578 --> 31:05.405
and he panics and he says, God, I don't know if I'm the right person for this.

31:05.485 --> 31:08.068
And we'll just pick it up briefly from verse 36.

31:08.429 --> 31:16.219
God, Gideon said to God, if you're going to rescue Israel through me as you have spoken, behold, I will put a fleece of wool on the threshing floor.

31:16.239 --> 31:22.788
If there is dew only on the fleece and it is dry on the ground, then I will know that you will rescue Israel from me as you have said.

31:23.549 --> 31:24.190
And it was so.

31:24.370 --> 31:26.613
And he gets up and he rings a whole bowl of water out of the fleece.

31:27.494 --> 31:30.258
And then Gideon said to God, don't let your anger burn against me.

31:30.370 --> 31:31.612
so that I may speak once more.

31:32.072 --> 31:34.576
Please let me make another test with the fleece.

31:34.596 --> 31:38.000
Now only let the fleece be dry and the dew be on the ground.

31:39.042 --> 31:44.268
And God did so that night for it was dry on the fleece and there was dew on the ground all around it.

31:46.231 --> 31:51.037
And this story gives me hope because things have started to get real for Gideon.

31:51.839 --> 31:54.482
I think we all know that feeling when you step out into something new

31:54.594 --> 32:05.708
and you suddenly realize what you've stepped out into and you can suddenly, it's that thing where you suddenly know what you don't know maybe if you start a new job after the first few weeks and you suddenly go, oh my gosh, reality hits and he hesitates.

32:07.410 --> 32:10.173
But God calls us even when we are hesitating.

32:11.715 --> 32:15.299
He's heard from God, he's taken a step out and he's come under fire.

32:16.381 --> 32:21.727
Things have gotten hard and the enemy has started to push back and Gideon is worried that maybe he made the wrong decision.

32:22.588 --> 32:24.050
Maybe he hasn't heard from God

32:24.258 --> 32:26.821
Because if he's wrong, the consequences will be dire.

32:28.082 --> 32:37.212
And so he asks for a sign in the morning dew that the fleece be wet and the ground be dry and God obliges, wakes up and the fleece is wet.

32:37.232 --> 32:42.137
But for Gideon, there is still this possibility that it could be a coincidence.

32:42.358 --> 32:44.300
It could just be chance.

32:44.961 --> 32:48.044
Because the hot ground is going to absorb moisture more quickly than the fleece.

32:48.544 --> 32:49.425
So it would kind of make sense.

32:49.445 --> 32:53.650
If you put a fleece on the ground on a dewy day, the ground might be dry and the fleece might be wet.

32:54.658 --> 32:57.162
So he asks God for confirmation for a second sign.

32:57.983 --> 33:00.967
Let the fleece be dry and the ground be wet.

33:02.709 --> 33:04.913
And the signs and the wonders are amazing in this story.

33:04.933 --> 33:08.097
But what I love is God's patience with Gideon and this.

33:09.519 --> 33:11.622
He doesn't scold him for not having enough faith.

33:12.223 --> 33:18.552
He's patient with him and he's gracious enough to confirm that this risky path is the path that he wants him to walk.

33:19.834 --> 33:22.738
Because stepping into the story doesn't mean that we won't ever waver.

33:23.234 --> 33:29.142
Hopefully, it won't be anything as serious as someone trying to kill you, but there are always consequences for stepping in.

33:29.803 --> 33:33.428
Because the enemy wants to keep us contained and he will use any tactic he can.

33:34.129 --> 33:37.733
And as soon as we step out, we're going to potentially be in the firing line.

33:39.375 --> 33:43.321
Gideon's wisdom here is to make sure that God really said.

33:43.481 --> 33:44.903
And I think there's two sides to this point.

33:45.644 --> 33:50.290
The first one is that God understands our doubts and is patient when we think we've heard from him.

33:51.010 --> 33:54.955
When it's that God, I really, I really need you to confirm this for me.

33:56.337 --> 33:59.642
And he will because he wants to use us, he wants to partner with us.

34:00.823 --> 34:10.817
But it's also a wise warning that says that it's easy to hear amazing stories of people doing amazing testimonies and incredible, crazy things for God and sometimes to get bit carried away.

34:11.798 --> 34:17.526
Because God isn't going to rush ahead of us if we're hesitating, but also we shouldn't rush ahead of him.

34:18.247 --> 34:20.530
Because none of us hears perfectly from God.

34:21.506 --> 34:28.213
It's really important that we step into the story that he wants us to step into because that is where our confidence and our security is.

34:28.974 --> 34:33.299
Not the story that we think sounds great or the story that we'd like to step into.

34:34.640 --> 34:37.664
Because God calls us even when we are hesitating.

34:40.727 --> 34:42.930
And that's where we're going to leave it with Gideon.

34:43.851 --> 34:45.993
But many of you will know the story that comes after.

34:46.714 --> 34:50.578
He amasses a vast army which God whistles down to just 300 men.

34:51.330 --> 34:54.614
so that no one could say that it wasn't God who gives them the victory.

34:56.457 --> 34:57.879
And they were, they were victorious.

34:58.880 --> 35:02.285
And for 40 years Gideon rules the people of Israel and there's peace.

35:03.366 --> 35:04.888
But eventually Gideon dies.

35:05.770 --> 35:08.674
And the people of Israel go right back to doing what they were doing.

35:09.675 --> 35:11.878
And the cycle that they are stuck in continues.

35:14.321 --> 35:17.746
And each judge, each judge that comes after Gideon, God uses them

35:19.138 --> 35:25.407
But when you read the book of Judges, there are some pretty awful people, Samson, Jepthor, they kind of get worse as the book goes on.

35:26.428 --> 35:35.320
And it's encouraging to know that God uses these people, these real people, with significant flaws to work through that, because he means that he can use me as well.

35:37.223 --> 35:43.712
But the flaws and the weaknesses and the doubts of the judges and the people, they eventually come back to bite them.

35:44.833 --> 35:48.338
God uses them, but their flaws eventually come back to them.

35:48.738 --> 35:54.026
And at the end of his life Gideon sets up an idol with all the gold that he's collected from the victory.

35:54.707 --> 36:02.839
And he sets this idol to worship and it is bigger and grander than the ones that he's torn down at the beginning of his story right when God called him.

36:04.001 --> 36:09.770
And the Bible says it's a snare for him and his family and the few people fall back into sin and the cycle continues.

36:11.472 --> 36:15.058
So why can we have any confidence when we step in?

36:16.540 --> 36:18.002
How do we know that when we step in

36:18.626 --> 36:27.457
that when we make a difference, that we offer what we have, that we're writing part of God's story rather than just the same cycle over and over and over again.

36:30.040 --> 36:35.166
And this is where I love judges as a book that it points to Jesus.

36:35.907 --> 36:38.591
Because we don't have a flawed judge that we follow.

36:39.131 --> 36:40.874
We don't even have a flawed king.

36:40.934 --> 36:44.498
We have a perfect king in Jesus.

36:44.642 --> 36:51.428
who Gideon, who Samson, who Deborah, who David, all of the others, they point to this perfect thing that will come.

36:51.468 --> 36:55.012
And it brings me back round as we finish to my point at the beginning.

36:56.793 --> 36:59.997
As Corinthians 2, 12 says, my grace is sufficient for you.

37:00.817 --> 37:03.700
My power is made perfect in weakness.

37:04.441 --> 37:11.888
Therefore, I will boast all the more gladly about my weaknesses so that Christ's power, Christ's power may rest on me.

37:13.429 --> 37:14.290
Jesus' power,

37:14.786 --> 37:19.732
Jesus grace, sorry, that's what breaks the cycle.

37:20.633 --> 37:32.547
Rather than rely on flawed earthly leaders and earthly kings, we have access to an all-powerful heavenly king and his Holy Spirit is in each one of us if we accept it.

37:32.568 --> 37:44.562
But rather than come back to bite me where I step in, where he calls me in my weaknesses, it's all better because Jesus power is made perfect, made perfect

37:45.026 --> 37:48.150
in my weaknesses and he uses them for his glory.

37:49.291 --> 37:51.253
That's the kind of story I want to step into church.

37:52.355 --> 37:59.203
And that's the kind of story I want to be part of, this topsy-turvy kingdom story where nobody is pushed out because they feel like they can't do it.

37:59.563 --> 38:08.754
Because if there's one thing I can say with absolute confidence is that every single person in this room has weaknesses that I am sure of, that's great.

38:09.575 --> 38:12.018
Because if we all have weaknesses that means we can all be used.

38:12.418 --> 38:17.045
Jesus can and will use those weaknesses for our glory if we let him.

38:18.408 --> 38:19.810
So let's not disqualify ourselves.

38:20.831 --> 38:28.784
Let's not think that stepping into the stories for somebody else, somebody better, somebody braver, somebody smarter, somebody who's not hiding, somebody who knows more.

38:28.824 --> 38:33.732
Let's not miss what God wants to do in our lives.

38:34.974 --> 38:39.922
For his power is made perfect in our weakness and therefore we

38:40.290 --> 38:45.917
will boast all the more gladly about our weaknesses that Christ's power may rest on us.

38:46.838 --> 38:48.039
Could I invite you to stand with me, Church?

39:00.895 --> 39:06.482
Lord Jesus, I thank you that you have a story that you are writing in and through each one of us.

39:07.394 --> 39:11.559
Thank you that you want and you call each one of us to step into that story with you.

39:13.541 --> 39:18.527
That our weaknesses are not things that are disqualified us, they are things that you will use for your glory.

39:21.250 --> 39:26.696
So Lord, I pray a courage that comes from knowing you over every person here today.

39:27.797 --> 39:35.826
Lord, where we hear Holy Spirit nudging from you, where it calls on us to do things that maybe we don't think we're good at, maybe we don't have it all together, maybe we are.

39:36.450 --> 39:39.573
afraid of looking silly or getting it wrong.

39:41.255 --> 39:47.262
God, I thank you that you give us the chance to partner with you in building the story of Jesus.

39:47.883 --> 39:56.993
I pray that we would hear your Holy Spirit call, Lord, that you are writing a story in each one of us through the gifts that you've given us and through the weaknesses that you want to use in us.

39:58.394 --> 40:04.401
Lord, as we go from this place, help us to hear that call and to step into those things in Jesus' name.

40:05.141 --> 40:05.682
Amen.

40:06.210 --> 40:06.772
Thanks, Josh.

